* Political Institutions and Offices | Republican Governance
What was the primary function of the Roman Senate? | Advised magistrates and shaped policy, especially foreign affairs and finance.
What was the normal term or duration for the Senate? | No fixed elected term; membership usually lifelong.
Name one defining power of the Senate. | Issued decrees and controlled major state finances.
Which office or body matches this note: Dominated by former magistrates from elite families. | Senate
Identify the Roman institution from this role: Advised magistrates and shaped policy, especially foreign affairs and finance. | Senate
What was the primary function of the Roman Consuls? | Highest annual magistrates leading government and armies.
What was the normal term or duration for the Consuls? | One year, with two serving simultaneously.
Name one defining power of the Consuls. | Imperium to command armies and convene Senate/assemblies.
Which office or body matches this note: Each consul could veto the other. | Consuls
Identify the Roman institution from this role: Highest annual magistrates leading government and armies. | Consuls
What was the primary function of the Roman Tribunes of the Plebs? | Protected plebeians against abuses by magistrates.
What was the normal term or duration for the Tribunes of the Plebs? | One year.
Name one defining power of the Tribunes of the Plebs. | Intercessio veto and sacrosanct personal status.
Which office or body matches this note: Could propose legislation to the Plebeian Council. | Tribunes of the Plebs
Identify the Roman institution from this role: Protected plebeians against abuses by magistrates. | Tribunes of the Plebs
What was the primary function of the Roman Praetors? | Senior magistrates primarily handling justice and legal administration.
What was the normal term or duration for the Praetors? | One year.
Name one defining power of the Praetors. | Imperium and authority to issue legal edicts.
Which office or body matches this note: Could govern provinces after office. | Praetors
Identify the Roman institution from this role: Senior magistrates primarily handling justice and legal administration. | Praetors
What was the primary function of the Roman Censors? | Conducted census and supervised public morals/contracts.
What was the normal term or duration for the Censors? | Usually elected every five years for an 18-month tenure.
Name one defining power of the Censors. | Could revise Senate rolls and assign tax contracts.
Which office or body matches this note: Prestigious office often held by ex-consuls. | Censors
Identify the Roman institution from this role: Conducted census and supervised public morals/contracts. | Censors
What was the primary function of the Roman Dictator? | Extraordinary magistrate for severe emergencies.
What was the normal term or duration for the Dictator? | Maximum six months, or until task completed.
Name one defining power of the Dictator. | Overrode normal collegial limits with supreme imperium.
Which office or body matches this note: Usually appointed by a consul on Senate advice. | Dictator
Identify the Roman institution from this role: Extraordinary magistrate for severe emergencies. | Dictator
What was the primary function of the Roman Comitia Centuriata? | Assembly voting by military/property groupings.
What was the normal term or duration for the Comitia Centuriata? | Met as needed, not fixed-term office.
Name one defining power of the Comitia Centuriata. | Elected higher magistrates and could pass laws.
Which office or body matches this note: Also declared war and heard certain capital cases. | Comitia Centuriata
Identify the Roman institution from this role: Assembly voting by military/property groupings. | Comitia Centuriata
* Law and Citizenship | Rights and Legal Order
What does this Roman legal concept refer to: Twelve Tables | Earliest public codification of Roman law (fifth century BCE).
Which concept matches this fact: Traditionally produced by the decemvirs. | Twelve Tables
Why is Twelve Tables significant in Roman legal history? | Made core legal norms publicly knowable.
What does this Roman legal concept refer to: Ius civile | Civil law specific to Roman citizens.
Which concept matches this fact: Applied in strict citizen legal relationships. | Ius civile
Why is Ius civile significant in Roman legal history? | Defined legal identity of Roman citizenship.
What does this Roman legal concept refer to: Ius gentium | Law of nations used in dealings with non-citizens and broader commerce.
Which concept matches this fact: Praetors used it to handle cross-cultural disputes. | Ius gentium
Why is Ius gentium significant in Roman legal history? | Helped standardize practical legal principles across empire.
What does this Roman legal concept refer to: Praetorian edict | Program of legal remedies announced by praetors.
Which concept matches this fact: Adapted legal practice beyond rigid old forms. | Praetorian edict
Why is Praetorian edict significant in Roman legal history? | Made Roman law more flexible and equitable.
What does this Roman legal concept refer to: Patria potestas | Legal authority of the male head of household.
Which concept matches this fact: Covered family members and property under family power. | Patria potestas
Why is Patria potestas significant in Roman legal history? | Core institution shaping Roman family law.
What does this Roman legal concept refer to: Manumission | Formal process of freeing a slave.
Which concept matches this fact: Freed persons became liberti with defined obligations. | Manumission
Why is Manumission significant in Roman legal history? | Linked slavery, citizenship pathways, and social mobility.
What does this Roman legal concept refer to: Civitas sine suffragio | Citizenship without full voting rights.
Which concept matches this fact: Used for integrating some communities into Roman system. | Civitas sine suffragio
Why is Civitas sine suffragio significant in Roman legal history? | Tool for gradual political incorporation.
What does this Roman legal concept refer to: Constitutio Antoniniana | Edict granting Roman citizenship to most free imperial inhabitants.
Which concept matches this fact: Issued by Caracalla in 212 CE. | Constitutio Antoniniana
Why is Constitutio Antoniniana significant in Roman legal history? | Greatly expanded the legal citizen body.
What does this Roman legal concept refer to: Provocatio | Right of appeal by citizens against certain magistrate punishments.
Which concept matches this fact: Important safeguard in Republican political culture. | Provocatio
Why is Provocatio significant in Roman legal history? | Early protection against arbitrary coercion.
What does this Roman legal concept refer to: Corpus Juris Civilis | Compilation of Roman law under Justinian (sixth century CE).
Which concept matches this fact: Includes Digest, Code, Institutes, and Novels. | Corpus Juris Civilis
Why is Corpus Juris Civilis significant in Roman legal history? | Preserved Roman jurisprudence for later legal traditions.
* Military Organization and Ranks | Army Structure
What was a Roman Legion? | Core heavy infantry formation of Roman army.
What size or composition best matches Legion? | Roughly 4,800-5,500 soldiers in many imperial periods.
Who typically commanded or led the Legion level? | Legatus legionis, under overall provincial command.
Which military term matches this clue: Citizen-heavy backbone of Roman field armies. | Legion
Identify the Roman military unit/role: Core heavy infantry formation of Roman army. | Legion
What was a Roman Cohort? | Major tactical subdivision of a legion.
What size or composition best matches Cohort? | Usually one-tenth of a legion; about 480 men in many cases.
Who typically commanded or led the Cohort level? | Centurions, with a senior centurion leading first cohort elements.
Which military term matches this clue: Replaced manipular structure as standard tactical block. | Cohort
Identify the Roman military unit/role: Major tactical subdivision of a legion. | Cohort
What was a Roman Century? | Basic infantry unit despite the name suggesting one hundred.
What size or composition best matches Century? | Typically around 80 men in imperial-era legions.
Who typically commanded or led the Century level? | Centurion.
Which military term matches this clue: Key command level for discipline and battlefield control. | Century
Identify the Roman military unit/role: Basic infantry unit despite the name suggesting one hundred. | Century
What was a Roman Contubernium? | Smallest tent-group in legion life.
What size or composition best matches Contubernium? | Usually 8 soldiers sharing gear and quarters.
Who typically commanded or led the Contubernium level? | Informal senior soldier influence rather than formal officer.
Which military term matches this clue: Fundamental unit of daily military life. | Contubernium
Identify the Roman military unit/role: Smallest tent-group in legion life. | Contubernium
What was a Roman Auxilia? | Non-legionary troops recruited largely from non-citizens.
What size or composition best matches Auxilia? | Varied cohorts/alae; often similar cohort sizes or cavalry wings.
Who typically commanded or led the Auxilia level? | Prefects and other appointed officers.
Which military term matches this clue: Provided cavalry, archers, and specialists. | Auxilia
Identify the Roman military unit/role: Non-legionary troops recruited largely from non-citizens. | Auxilia
What was a Roman Praetorian Guard? | Elite guard force tied to emperor's protection.
What size or composition best matches Praetorian Guard? | Several cohorts stationed primarily near Rome.
Who typically commanded or led the Praetorian Guard level? | Praetorian prefect.
Which military term matches this clue: Could influence imperial succession politics. | Praetorian Guard
Identify the Roman military unit/role: Elite guard force tied to emperor's protection. | Praetorian Guard
What was a Roman Limes? | Frontier defense system of forts, roads, and barriers.
What size or composition best matches Limes? | Not a single unit; a regional military network.
Who typically commanded or led the Limes level? | Provincial commanders and local garrisons.
Which military term matches this clue: Associated with borders like the Rhine-Danube frontiers. | Limes
Identify the Roman military unit/role: Frontier defense system of forts, roads, and barriers. | Limes
* Religion, Gods, Rituals, Cults | Belief and Practice
Who or what is Jupiter in Roman religion? | Chief god associated with sky, thunder, and sovereignty.
Which religious term matches this fact: Part of Capitoline Triad with Juno and Minerva. | Jupiter
Why was Jupiter significant in Roman public life? | Symbolized divine backing of Roman state authority.
Who or what is Juno in Roman religion? | Major goddess linked to marriage and protection of women.
Which religious term matches this fact: Member of Capitoline Triad. | Juno
Why was Juno significant in Roman public life? | Important in civic cult and household rites.
Who or what is Minerva in Roman religion? | Goddess of wisdom, crafts, and strategic thought.
Which religious term matches this fact: Associated with artisans and intellectual pursuits. | Minerva
Why was Minerva significant in Roman public life? | Connected practical skill with divine favor.
Who or what is Mars in Roman religion? | God of war and an ancestral figure in Roman myth.
Which religious term matches this fact: Father of Romulus and Remus in tradition. | Mars
Why was Mars significant in Roman public life? | Linked military success to sacred duty.
Who or what is Vesta in Roman religion? | Goddess of hearth and sacred domestic/public fire.
Which religious term matches this fact: Her eternal flame was tended by Vestal Virgins. | Vesta
Why was Vesta significant in Roman public life? | Represented continuity and safety of the Roman state.
Who or what is Vestal Virgins in Roman religion? | Priestesses of Vesta sworn to long chastity service.
Which religious term matches this fact: Maintained sacred fire in the Forum. | Vestal Virgins
Why was Vestal Virgins significant in Roman public life? | Their status tied ritual purity to civic security.
Who or what is Pontifex Maximus in Roman religion? | Highest priestly office in Roman religion.
Which religious term matches this fact: Held by leading statesmen and later emperors. | Pontifex Maximus
Why was Pontifex Maximus significant in Roman public life? | Showed fusion of religion and political authority.
Who or what is Augury in Roman religion? | Divination through interpretation of bird signs.
Which religious term matches this fact: Performed by augurs before major acts. | Augury
Why was Augury significant in Roman public life? | Provided ritual legitimacy for public decisions.
Who or what is Imperial cult in Roman religion? | Worship practices honoring emperors and Roma.
Which religious term matches this fact: Expanded especially in provinces. | Imperial cult
Why was Imperial cult significant in Roman public life? | Reinforced loyalty and imperial cohesion.
Who or what is Saturnalia in Roman religion? | Festival honoring Saturn with role reversals and gift-giving.
Which religious term matches this fact: Celebrated in December with feasting. | Saturnalia
Why was Saturnalia significant in Roman public life? | Illustrates social release within Roman religious calendar.
* Daily Life, Family, Social Classes | Society and Routine
What does this Roman social term mean: Paterfamilias | Legal male head of household with broad family authority.
Give one key detail about Paterfamilias in daily life. | Managed property and family decisions under patria potestas.
How did Paterfamilias relate to broader Roman society? | Anchored hierarchy in Roman domestic structure.
Which daily-life concept matches this clue: Household authority centered in one senior male. | Paterfamilias
Identify the Roman term from this description: Legal male head of household with broad family authority. | Paterfamilias
What does this Roman social term mean: Domus | Townhouse of wealthier Roman families.
Give one key detail about Domus in daily life. | Often included atrium, peristyle, and reception areas.
How did Domus relate to broader Roman society? | Displayed status and patronage relationships.
Which daily-life concept matches this clue: Elite urban residence with formal household spaces. | Domus
Identify the Roman term from this description: Townhouse of wealthier Roman families. | Domus
What does this Roman social term mean: Insulae | Multi-story apartment blocks common for urban residents.
Give one key detail about Insulae in daily life. | Could be crowded and vulnerable to fire or collapse.
How did Insulae relate to broader Roman society? | Housed much of non-elite city population.
Which daily-life concept matches this clue: Typical housing for many in imperial Rome. | Insulae
Identify the Roman term from this description: Multi-story apartment blocks common for urban residents. | Insulae
What does this Roman social term mean: Patricians and Plebeians | Traditional social distinction between aristocratic lineages and common citizens.
Give one key detail about Patricians and Plebeians in daily life. | Political struggle shaped early Republican institutions.
How did Patricians and Plebeians relate to broader Roman society? | Class identity influenced offices, marriage, and influence.
Which daily-life concept matches this clue: Early Roman social division central to republican history. | Patricians and Plebeians
Identify the Roman term from this description: Traditional social distinction between aristocratic lineages and common citizens. | Patricians and Plebeians
What does this Roman social term mean: Toga and Tunic | Basic clothing pattern where tunic was everyday wear and toga formal male citizen dress.
Give one key detail about Toga and Tunic in daily life. | Toga signaled civic status in public settings.
How did Toga and Tunic relate to broader Roman society? | Dress communicated rank and legal identity.
Which daily-life concept matches this clue: Formal draped garment linked to male citizenship. | Toga and Tunic
Identify the Roman term from this description: Basic clothing pattern where tunic was everyday wear and toga formal male citizen dress. | Toga and Tunic
What does this Roman social term mean: Thermae | Public bath complexes for hygiene, exercise, and socializing.
Give one key detail about Thermae in daily life. | Included hot, warm, and cold rooms.
How did Thermae relate to broader Roman society? | Functioned as social hubs across class lines.
Which daily-life concept matches this clue: Bath culture central to urban Roman routine. | Thermae
Identify the Roman term from this description: Public bath complexes for hygiene, exercise, and socializing. | Thermae
What does this Roman social term mean: Amphitheater Games | Public spectacles including gladiatorial combat and beast hunts.
Give one key detail about Amphitheater Games in daily life. | Sponsored by elites/emperors for prestige and popularity.
How did Amphitheater Games relate to broader Roman society? | Entertainment also conveyed political messaging.
Which daily-life concept matches this clue: Mass venue events tied to public favor. | Amphitheater Games
Identify the Roman term from this description: Public spectacles including gladiatorial combat and beast hunts. | Amphitheater Games
* Architecture and Engineering | Built Roman World
What is a Roman Aqueduct? | Engineered water channel system bringing water to cities.
What was the main purpose of Roman Aqueduct? | Supplied baths, fountains, and households.
Name a key technical feature of Roman Aqueduct. | Maintained steady gradients over long distances.
Which architectural concept fits this example: Aqua Claudia and Pont du Gard are famous cases. | Aqueduct
Identify the Roman engineering element: Engineered water channel system bringing water to cities. | Aqueduct
What is a Roman Roman Roads? | Durable road network connecting cities, forts, and ports.
What was the main purpose of Roman Roman Roads? | Enabled rapid troop movement and trade.
Name a key technical feature of Roman Roman Roads. | Layered construction improved drainage and longevity.
Which architectural concept fits this example: Via Appia is one of the best known routes. | Roman Roads
Identify the Roman engineering element: Durable road network connecting cities, forts, and ports. | Roman Roads
What is a Roman Arch? | Curved structural form distributing weight efficiently.
What was the main purpose of Roman Arch? | Supported bridges, gates, and monumental works.
Name a key technical feature of Roman Arch. | Keystone-centered load transfer.
Which architectural concept fits this example: Seen in triumphal arches and aqueduct arcades. | Arch
Identify the Roman engineering element: Curved structural form distributing weight efficiently. | Arch
What is a Roman Amphitheater? | Oval venue for large public spectacles.
What was the main purpose of Roman Amphitheater? | Hosted gladiator combats and venationes.
Name a key technical feature of Roman Amphitheater. | Tiered seating with engineered crowd circulation.
Which architectural concept fits this example: The Colosseum is the most famous example. | Amphitheater
Identify the Roman engineering element: Oval venue for large public spectacles. | Amphitheater
What is a Roman Basilica? | Large public hall used for law, commerce, and administration.
What was the main purpose of Roman Basilica? | Provided covered civic space near forum life.
Name a key technical feature of Roman Basilica. | Long nave-like hall with aisles.
Which architectural concept fits this example: Basilica Aemilia and Basilica Ulpia are examples. | Basilica
Identify the Roman engineering element: Large public hall used for law, commerce, and administration. | Basilica
What is a Roman Bath Complex? | Large public facility for bathing and leisure.
What was the main purpose of Roman Bath Complex? | Combined hygiene, exercise, and social functions.
Name a key technical feature of Roman Bath Complex. | Hypocaust heating system for warm rooms.
Which architectural concept fits this example: Baths of Caracalla show imperial scale. | Bath Complex
Identify the Roman engineering element: Large public facility for bathing and leisure. | Bath Complex
What is a Roman Roman Concrete? | Building material using lime mortar and volcanic ash.
What was the main purpose of Roman Roman Concrete? | Enabled massive domes and durable harbor works.
Name a key technical feature of Roman Roman Concrete. | Pozzolanic reaction gave strength and longevity.
Which architectural concept fits this example: Critical to structures like the Pantheon dome. | Roman Concrete
Identify the Roman engineering element: Building material using lime mortar and volcanic ash. | Roman Concrete
* Literature, Philosophy, Historians | Texts and Ideas
Which Roman author is associated with Aeneid? | Virgil
What genre best describes Aeneid by Virgil? | Epic poetry
Name one key fact about Virgil. | Commissioned in Augustan age and central to Roman literary identity.
Which Roman author is associated with Metamorphoses? | Ovid
What genre best describes Metamorphoses by Ovid? | Mythological narrative poetry
Name one key fact about Ovid. | Exiled by Augustus to Tomis.
Which Roman author is associated with Odes? | Horace
What genre best describes Odes by Horace? | Lyric poetry
Name one key fact about Horace. | Known for polished verse and patronage by Maecenas.
Which Roman author is associated with Ab Urbe Condita? | Livy
What genre best describes Ab Urbe Condita by Livy? | History
Name one key fact about Livy. | Wrote monumental history of Rome from its origins.
Which Roman author is associated with Annals? | Tacitus
What genre best describes Annals by Tacitus? | History
Name one key fact about Tacitus. | Noted for sharp analysis of imperial power.
Which Roman author is associated with The Twelve Caesars? | Suetonius
What genre best describes The Twelve Caesars by Suetonius? | Biography
Name one key fact about Suetonius. | Compiled imperial lives rich in anecdote.
Which Roman author is associated with Philippics? | Cicero
What genre best describes Philippics by Cicero? | Oratory and political prose
Name one key fact about Cicero. | Major stylist of Latin prose and republican statesman.
Which Roman author is associated with Letters to Lucilius? | Seneca
What genre best describes Letters to Lucilius by Seneca? | Stoic philosophy
Name one key fact about Seneca. | Tutor and advisor to Nero at one point.
Which Roman author is associated with Natural History? | Pliny the Elder
What genre best describes Natural History by Pliny the Elder? | Encyclopedic prose
Name one key fact about Pliny the Elder. | Died during rescue efforts in Vesuvius eruption.
Which Roman author is associated with Letters? | Pliny the Younger
What genre best describes Letters by Pliny the Younger? | Epistolary prose
Name one key fact about Pliny the Younger. | Described Vesuvius eruption and provincial administration.
* Economy, Trade, Coinage, Taxation | Money and Markets
What does this Roman economic term mean: Denarius | Widely used Roman silver coin for much of imperial history.
How did Denarius function in practice? | Used in military pay and market exchange.
Why was Denarius important to the Roman economy? | Served as a standard monetary reference across regions.
What does this Roman economic term mean: Aureus | High-value Roman gold coin.
How did Aureus function in practice? | Used for large payments, state finance, and elite transactions.
Why was Aureus important to the Roman economy? | Signaled imperial fiscal capacity and prestige.
What does this Roman economic term mean: Sestertius | Common accounting and coin denomination in Roman economy.
How did Sestertius function in practice? | Frequently used in pricing and inscriptions.
Why was Sestertius important to the Roman economy? | Useful benchmark for wages, costs, and public spending.
What does this Roman economic term mean: Tax Farming | System where private contractors collected taxes.
How did Tax Farming function in practice? | Publicani paid state in advance then collected revenues.
Why was Tax Farming important to the Roman economy? | Generated funds quickly but could encourage abuse.
What does this Roman economic term mean: Annona | State grain supply system, especially for Rome.
How did Annona function in practice? | Organized transport and distribution of grain imports.
Why was Annona important to the Roman economy? | Helped stabilize urban food supply and politics.
What does this Roman economic term mean: Latifundia | Large landed estates often worked by slaves or tenants.
How did Latifundia function in practice? | Produced agricultural surplus for markets.
Why was Latifundia important to the Roman economy? | Concentrated landownership and influenced social tensions.
What does this Roman economic term mean: Mediterranean Trade Network | Sea routes linking provinces for bulk goods exchange.
How did Mediterranean Trade Network function in practice? | Shipping moved grain, oil, wine, and pottery at scale.
Why was Mediterranean Trade Network important to the Roman economy? | Integrated imperial regions into one economic sphere.
What does this Roman economic term mean: Port Infrastructure | Harbors, warehouses, and quays supporting commerce.
How did Port Infrastructure function in practice? | Facilities like Ostia handled imports to Rome.
Why was Port Infrastructure important to the Roman economy? | Reduced transport bottlenecks for urban supply.
What does this Roman economic term mean: State Minting | Imperial authority over coin production and imagery.
How did State Minting function in practice? | Mints struck coins with official legends and portraits.
Why was State Minting important to the Roman economy? | Broadcast political messages while supplying currency.
What does this Roman economic term mean: Tribute and Provincial Taxes | Regular fiscal obligations from provinces.
How did Tribute and Provincial Taxes function in practice? | Collected in cash and kind depending on region.
Why was Tribute and Provincial Taxes important to the Roman economy? | Financed armies, administration, and public works.
